%BOM---------------------
Date:7/23/2007 11:45:57 AM
From:Jurgis Bekepuris
I hold about 40 stocks right now and I am looking to keep the same number or
reduce it a bit in the future. I am holding a few sector bets as stocks -
mostly energy related. Stocks constitute about 1/3 of my total investments.
Other 2/3 is mutual funds, but I am reducing this number.

Right now I am trying to eliminate or increase positions that constitute less
than 1% of my total investments (~3% of stocks).

Mutual funds I hold come in 3 varieties: a) accounts where I cannot hold
stocks, b) sector and market bets (energy, India, China) c) investments in
areas that I don't understand, but agree to be profitable. For example, I am
very different value investor from Marty Whitman, so I hold TAVFX as a
"different" value investment.

I never could figure out which of 2 stocks would be a "better" investment. I
can only operate in absolute terms: I know when a stock is a buy and I know
when a stock is a sell. If it is a buy, I buy a starter position (~1% of my
total investments) and increase it if the stock drops (usually, I double on
every 20% drop).

If stock is a sell, I sell the whole position. I also sometimes sell if stock
appreciates fast 20-30% from my buy price with no positive business
developments. On outsized positions, I may trim the position before the sell
point is reached. I also sell, if business materially changes or if I no longer
can understand or support holding the position.

I do no conscious diversification or risk management. I agree with Buffett on
this: if a stock is undervalued, it has low risk, if it is fairly valued to
overvalued, it has a high risk. That's it. ;) Volatility is not risk (I think
this one comes from Marty Whitman or was it Bill Miller? ;)).
