I found this all a very fascinating discussion. On the basis of the inputs from
most who partook, my takeaway is that most investors who manage their own
accounts have anywhere from 30 to 50 holdings and are more focused on the
individual issues in their portfolios than on any large macro theme involving
diversification or value. The normal distribution on the bell curve seems to
imply that the outliers are more like yourself and Dale with more issues, and
some on the low end of the spectrum as well with only a few issues.

I guess striking the correct balance is an individual issue, and perhaps a
learned response based on experience. Only the individual managing there own
portfolio can say what's right for them when they take a look at their own
performance over time in terms of wealth building and increases in value.

I do agree with your concept of planting a few seeds for later harvest. But
becoming a farmer goes beyond that. Good food for thought and introspective
analysis. We all have to look in the mirror and say, what am I doing right, or
in lieu, what am I doing wrong.

